<h2 id="Chapter-1.--Generating-Oncogenic-Activation-Signature"><strong>Chapter 1.  Generating Oncogenic Activation Signature</strong><a class="anchor-link" href="http://localhost:8888/notebooks/OncoGPS_Analysis_paper/notebooks/1%20Generating%20Oncogenic%20Activation%20Signature.ipynb#Chapter-1.--Generating-Oncogenic-Activation-Signature">¶</a></h2>

Mesirov<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>^<span class="cm-bracket">{</span><span class="cm-atom">2</span>, 3<span class="cm-bracket">}</span><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span> and Pablo Tamayo<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>^<span class="cm-bracket">{</span><span class="cm-atom">2</span>,3<span class="cm-bracket">}</span><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>.</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-variable-2">1. Eli and Edythe Broad Institute</span><span class="cm-variable-2 cm-trailing-space-a"> </span><span class="cm-variable-2 cm-trailing-space-b"> </span><span class="cm-variable-2 cm-trailing-space-a"> </span><span class="cm-variable-2 cm-trailing-space-b"> </span><span class="cm-variable-2 cm-trailing-space-a"> </span><span class="cm-variable-2 cm-trailing-space-new-line"> </span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-variable-2">2. UCSD Moores Cancer Center</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-variable-2">3. UCSD School of Medicine </span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-strong">**Date:**</span> April 17, 2017</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-strong">**Article:**</span> <span class="cm-link">[</span><span class="cm-em cm-link">*Kim et al.*</span><span class="cm-link"> Decomposing Oncogenic Transcriptional Signatures to Generate Maps of Divergent Cellular States]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B0MQqMWLrsA4b2RUTTAzNjFmVkk/view?usp=sharing)</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-strong">**Analysis overview**</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">In this chapter we will execute the first step in the Onco-GPS methodology: generating the oncogenic activation signature.</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-tag cm-bracket">&lt;</span><span class="cm-tag">img</span> <span class="cm-attribute">src</span>=<span class="cm-string">"../media/method_chap1.png"</span> <span class="cm-attribute">width</span>=<span class="cm-string">2144</span> <span class="cm-attribute">height</span>=<span class="cm-string">1041</span><span class="cm-tag cm-bracket">&gt;</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"> </span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">The Onco-GPS method makes use of a signature from an isogenic system that provides clean and direct transcriptional information relevant to the transcriptional changes associated with the activation of an oncogene; while at the same time incorporating diverse regulatory circuits inherently represented across multiple cellular contexts in a reference dataset. This deconvolves the functional consequences of oncogene activation in a more direct and unambiguous way. </span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">In this notebook we will generate a KRAS signature based on RNASeq profiling of lentiviral constructs of KRAS mut G12 vs. controls in lung SALE epithelial cell lines. We performed pilot experiments to identify optimal set of conditions (time, viral titer) to carry out the  experiments. This KRAS signature will contain the set of top 1,000 differentially expressed genes, (top 500, bottom 500), according to the Information Coefficient (IC).  The Information Coefficient (IC) (<span class="cm-link">[</span><span class="cm-em cm-link">*Linfoot 1957*</span><span class="cm-link">]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S001999585790116X)</span>; <span class="cm-link">[</span><span class="cm-em cm-link">*Joe 1989*</span><span class="cm-link">]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(https://www.jstor.org/stable/2289859?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents)</span>; <span class="cm-link">[</span><span class="cm-em cm-link">*Kim, J.W., Botvinnik 2016*</span><span class="cm-link">]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4868596/)</span>) is a normalized version of the mutual information defined as,</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>IC(x, y) = sign(\rho(x,y)) \sqrt[]{ (1 - \exp(2I(x,y))} <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">where <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>I(x, y)<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>  is the differential mutual information between <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>x<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>, the KRAS mut vs. cntrl binary phenotype, and <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>y<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>, the expression profile for each gene. This quantity  lies in the range [-1, 1], in analogy with the correlation coefficient. The sign of the correlation coefficient <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span><span class="cm-tag">\rho</span>(x, y)<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span> is used to provide directionality. The differential <span class="cm-link">[mutual Information]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutual_information)</span> <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>I(x, y)<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>  is a function of the ratio of joint and marginal probabilities, </span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>I(x,y) = \int \int P(x, y) \log \frac{P(x,y)}{P(x)P(y)} dx dy = H(x, y) - H(x) - H(y).<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span><span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">The <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>H(x,y)<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span>, <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>H(x)<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span> and <span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-open">$</span>H(y)<span class="cm-delimit cm-delimit-close">$</span> are the joint and marginal <span class="cm-link">[entropies]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entropy_(information_theory)</span>. Estimating the mutual information between a phenotype and gene expression profiles requires the empirical approximation of continuous probability density distributions using kernel <span class="cm-link">[density estimators]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Density_estimation)</span> (<span class="cm-link">[</span><span class="cm-em cm-link">*Sheather 2004*</span><span class="cm-link">]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(http://www.stat.washington.edu/courses/stat527/s13/readings/Sheather_StatSci_2004.pdf)</span>).</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">Go to the <span class="cm-link">[next chapter (2)]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(2 Decomposing Signature and Defining Transcriptional Components.ipynb)</span>.</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;">Back to the <span class="cm-link">[introduction chapter (0)]</span><span class="cm-string cm-url">(0 Introduction and Overview.ipynb)</span>.</span></pre><pre class=" CodeMirror-line "><span style="padding-right: 0.1px;"><span cm-text="">​</span></span></pre></div></div></div></div></div><div style="position: absolute; height: 21px; width: 1px; border-bottom: 0px solid transparent; top: 807px;"></div><div class="CodeMirror-gutters" style="display: none; height: 828px;"></div></div></div></div><div class="text_cell_render rendered_html" tabindex="-1"><p><strong>Authors:</strong> William Kim<span class="MathJax_Preview" style="color: inherit;"></span><span class="MathJax" id="MathJax-Element-20-Frame" tabindex="0" data-mathml="&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow class=&quot;MJX-TeXAtom-ORD&quot;&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/math&gt;" role="presentation" style="position: relative;"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-214" role="math" style="width: 0.466em; <p><strong>Date:</strong> April 17, 2017</p>
<p><strong>Article:</strong> <a href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B0MQqMWLrsA4b2RUTTAzNjFmVkk/view?usp=sharing" target="_blank"><em>Kim et al.</em> Decomposing Oncogenic Transcriptional Signatures to Generate Maps of Divergent Cellular States</a></p>
<p><strong>Analysis overview</strong></p>
<p>In this chapter we will execute the first step in the Onco-GPS methodology: generating the oncogenic activation signature.</p>
<p><img src="./1 Generating Oncogenic Activation Signature_files/method_chap1.png" width="2144" height="1041">
 
The Onco-GPS method makes use of a signature from an isogenic system that provides clean and direct transcriptional information relevant to the transcriptional changes associated with the activation of an oncogene; while at the same time incorporating diverse regulatory circuits inherently represented across multiple cellular contexts in a reference dataset. This deconvolves the functional consequences of oncogene activation in a more direct and unambiguous way. </p>
<p>In this notebook we will generate a KRAS signature based on RNASeq profiling of lentiviral constructs of KRAS mut G12 vs. controls in lung SALE epithelial cell lines. We performed pilot experiments to identify optimal set of conditions (time, viral titer) to carry out the  experiments. This KRAS signature will contain the set of top 1,000 differentially expressed genes, (top 500, bottom 500), according to the Information Coefficient (IC).  The Information Coefficient (IC) (<a href="http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S001999585790116X" target="_blank"><em>Linfoot 1957</em></a>; <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2289859?seq=1#page_scan_tab_contents" target="_blank"><em>Joe 1989</em></a>; <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4868596/" target="_blank"><em>Kim, J.W., Botvinnik 2016</em></a>) is a normalized version of the mutual information defined as,</p>

<p>The <span class="MathJax_Preview" style="color: inherit;"></span><span class="MathJax" id="MathJax-Element-36-Frame" tabindex="0" data-mathml="&lt;math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&quot;false&quot;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&quot;false&quot;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/math&gt;" role="presentation" style="position: relative;"><nobr aria-hidden="true"><span class="math" id="MathJax-Span-407" role="math" style="width: 3.038em; <p>This is the main function used in this notebook. It computes the association between the phenotype and the gene expression profiles as described in the introduction above. At completion this function will produce a heatmap (SIGNATURE.pdf) and a text file (SIGNATURE.txt) where the genes have been sorted by their association with the phenotype as measured by the IC. The function also computes a bootstrap confidence interval for the IC (shown in parenthesis) and the p-values and False Discovery Rates (FDR) using an empirical permutations test (using <em>n_permutations</em> times the number of genes). The heatmap below shows the 20 genes on top (UP) and at the bottom (DOWN) of the list. The gene names are on the left of the heatmap. This computation takes a few hours and therefore it is desirable to run overnight.</p>
